    <p>Looking at this table, you will notice that the stroke savings range from 3 to 11 strokes per character. On average, simplified characters use about <strong>30-40% fewer strokes</strong> than their traditional counterparts. For high-frequency characters used hundreds of times per page, this adds up to significant time savings when handwriting — though with digital typing now dominant, this practical advantage has diminished.</p>
    <p>Also observe that some simplifications are more intuitive than others. 門→门 clearly simplifies the door shape. 龍→龙 is dramatically different and requires memorizing a new form. Characters with systematic radical simplifications (語→语, 話→话) are the easiest to learn as a set because the pattern is consistent.</p>
    <p>Try converting characters yourself with our <a href="/chinese/tools/traditional-simplified/">Traditional/Simplified Converter tool</a>. Paste any Chinese text and instantly see both versions side by side.</p>

    <h2 id="where-used">Where Each System Is Used Today</h2>

