    <p>In practice, most online platforms support both systems. WeChat, Weibo, and Chinese websites from mainland China use simplified. Taiwanese news sites, forums, and government documents use traditional. Google Translate and most digital tools can convert between them automatically.</p>
    <p>An interesting middle ground exists in <strong>Japanese</strong>, which uses its own simplified kanji (新字体) that overlap with some Chinese simplified characters but not others. For example, Japanese simplified 学 (from 學) matches Chinese simplified, but Japanese 気 (from 氣) differs from Chinese simplified 气. Learners studying both Chinese and Japanese should be aware of these three-way differences.</p>
    <p>In the <strong>academic and literary world</strong>, traditional characters remain important regardless of your primary system. Classical Chinese texts, historical documents, calligraphy, and academic papers on Chinese linguistics often use traditional characters. Even mainland Chinese scholars need to read traditional characters for research purposes. This is why many universities in mainland China include traditional character literacy in their Chinese language curriculum.</p>

    <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Advantages and Disadvantages of Each System</h2>

    <table style="width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin:1.5rem 0;font-size:0.95rem">
